# Dart Style Guide

## Formatting

- Run `dart format .` before every commit — enforced by CI.
- Line length: 80 (dart format default). No manual wrapping needed.
- Always use trailing commas on multi-line argument lists.

## Imports

Always use **package imports** (`package:rego/...`), never relative imports outside of the same directory.

```dart
// ✅
import 'package:rego/core/theme/app_colors.dart';

// ❌
import '../../../core/theme/app_colors.dart';
```

Sort imports: dart → flutter → packages → project (dart format handles this with `dart fix`).

## Types and nullability

- Prefer explicit types on public APIs; let inference work for local variables.
- Never use `dynamic` unless unavoidable (JSON deserialization). Annotate with `// ignore: avoid_dynamic_calls` if Dio forces it.
- Use `?.` and `??` instead of null checks where possible.

## Const and final

- Mark constructors `const` whenever all fields are final and compile-time constant.
- Mark widget fields `final`.
- `const` widget constructors dramatically reduce rebuilds.

## Classes

```dart
// ✅ Abstract final for static utility classes (no accidental instantiation)
abstract final class AppColors { ... }

// ✅ Freezed for data classes
@freezed
class User with _$User {
  const factory User({required String id, required String name}) = _User;
  factory User.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) => _$UserFromJson(json);
}
```

## Error handling

- Use typed exceptions or `sealed` result types — not bare `catch (e)`.
- Surface errors via `AsyncValue.error` in providers, not try/catch in widgets.
- Log errors; don't swallow them silently.

## Comments

- Only comment the **why**, not the what.
- Good: `// Drift requires a unique name per accessor — reusing trips a compile error.`
- Bad: `// Get the user` (the method name already says that).
- No multi-line block comments. One line max.

## Tests

- File mirrors the source tree: `test/features/home/presentation/home_screen_test.dart`.
- Name tests as sentences: `test('shows empty state when list is empty', ...)`.
- Use `flutter_test` for widget tests; `test` package for pure Dart unit tests.
